{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/no-slicer-selected-no-chart-in-power-bi-17ce5d36cd40", "time": 1683014313.541892, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/no-slicer-selected-no-chart-in-power-bi-17ce5d36cd40/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "No slicer selected \u2014 No chart in Power BI | by Nikola Ilic | Towards Data Science", "h1": "No slicer selected \u2014 No chart in Power BI", "description": "When working with Power BI on a daily basis, from time to time I like to \u201cchallenge\u201d the tool and see how it behaves in some non-standard set-ups. I mean, we all like when our task is done in a short\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/how-i-speed-up-my-power-bi-report-5x-155255415895", "anchor_text": "\u201cchallenge\u201d the tool", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/5-tips-to-boost-your-power-bi-development-a44d7e782037", "anchor_text": "whole variety of features", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dax/isfiltered-function-dax", "anchor_text": "ISFILTERED()", "paragraph_index": 4}, {"url": "https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dax/allselected-function-dax", "anchor_text": "ALLSELECTED()", "paragraph_index": 7}, {"url": "https://www.sqlbi.com/articles/the-definitive-guide-to-allselected/", "anchor_text": "this article", "paragraph_index": 7}, {"url": "https://datamozart.medium.com/membership", "anchor_text": "Become a member and read every story on Medium!", "paragraph_index": 19}, {"url": "http://eepurl.com/gOH8iP", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 20}, {"url": "http://data-mozart.com", "anchor_text": "data-mozart.com", "paragraph_index": 22}], "all_paragraphs": ["When working with Power BI on a daily basis, from time to time I like to \u201cchallenge\u201d the tool and see how it behaves in some non-standard set-ups. I mean, we all like when our task is done in a short period of time, and Power BI has a whole variety of features to help us achieve that, but sometimes I feel like changing the default behavior can enhance user experience.", "Let\u2019s say that I want a create a chart that will show-up ONLY when at least one specific value is selected within the slicer. As usual, I will use the sample Contoso database for demo purposes.", "As you probably know, by default, if no specific value is selected within the slicer, Power BI will show figures for all the slicer values:", "Now, the idea is to hide these bars until at least one selection is made within a slicer. If that\u2019s not the case, we want to show a blank chart. How can we achieve that?", "We will use ISFILTERED() function to check if the specified column is being directly filtered. In our case, it\u2019s the column BrandName from the Product dimension. The result of the function is of boolean type (TRUE/FALSE).", "I will put this measure in the card visual, just to check if everything works as expected:", "And once I select a specific value within the slicer, my measure will return a different result:", "The next thing we need to do is to remove the current filter context. For that purpose, we will use ALLSELECTED() function. This is quite a complex function, that can be used for various different things, so I recommend you to read this article from Marco Russo and Alberto Ferrari if you want to fully understand ALLSELECTED() function.", "Basically, nothing will change in the current look of our report, but we\u2019ve expanded the logic of our measure and laid the ground for the final goal we are trying to achieve.", "Now, let\u2019s create our final measure:", "Let me stop for a moment and explain what are we doing here: by using IF, we can control the final result of the measure. Simply said, if the result of our previously created measure Filtered Brands is TRUE, we want to return the Sales Amt measure value; if not, we are returning BLANKs.", "Even though we achieved our original goal, this may seem counter-intuitive at first sight. Imagine the user\u2019s reaction when he opens a report and sees a blank visual with the default slicer set-up! I bet you would get some calls, complaining that something is broken\u2026", "So, let\u2019s make this final touch to make our users happy! The first thing I\u2019m gonna do is to create a measure which will hold the message for my users:", "Again, the IF function will allow us to define the flow: if the user made a selection within the slicer, it will return an empty string; if not, it will display the specified text.", "Now, let\u2019s put a card visual on the report canvas, place our Message measure in it, and do some important adjustments in the Format pane of the card visual:", "We will turn off Category and set Transparency to 100%. When I put the card visual over my Clustered Column Chart, I will see my message displayed over it, that instructs the user what he needs to do. Once he selects a value, or values, within the Brand slicer, he will see data bars appear instead of the message.", "Let\u2019s check if that works as expected:", "As I always like to emphasize, Power BI is an amazing tool! It gives you the flexibility to tell the data story in multiple different ways. This example has shown how you can easily change the default set-up and customize the look and feel of your report, depending on the specific business requests.", "Of course, you should not use this trick in every single scenario \u2014 honestly, in 99% cases, you should stick with the default behavior. But, it\u2019s nice to have another tool under your belt, and that you know that you can use it to customize your Power BI reports.", "Become a member and read every story on Medium!", "Subscribe here to get more insightful data articles!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Data Mozart \u2014 Make Music from your Data!| data-mozart.com | @DataMozart | Microsoft Data Platform MVP | Power BI Addict | Blogger, speaker, learner\u2026"], "all_out